Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11160: loaded teachpacks must be Run before available
Date: Sat, 4 Sep 2010 10:46:26 -0500

 On Sat, Sep 4, 2010 at 10:39 AM, Matthias Felleisen
 <matthias@ccs.neu.edu> wrote:
 >
 > Initializing the language and the teachpacks shouldn't have any effects, so I don't understand your objection.
 
 Should not and do not are different things. Since teachpacks come from
 source we don't control, I'm leery of that. Don't forget that anyone
 can add any module at any time as a teachpack and then the body of
 that module will run each time someone then opens a file for editing.
 
 While it seems unlikely that the body of the teachpack does "rm -rf
 /", it could easily do something that takes time and thus make
 DrRacket seem sluggish (esp on windows when touching the file system
 can easily involve the network and permissions errors that take time
 to report, etc).
 
 > My objection to option b is this:
 >
 > -- a student may recall that teachpack T is specified with file F
 > -- he opens file F
 > -- drracket doesn't show T in the status line
 > -- student says "silly dr, can't even remember which teachpacks I used"
 > -- student uses menu Language/Select teachpack, and low and behold, 'clear teachpack T' is visible
 >
 > This means the dr does remember something about teachpacks and there is an inconsistency between model and view. Or the student is justifiedly dissing the dr's support.
 
 There is no inconsistency between model and view here, only
 inconsistency between the student's opinion of what the model should
 be and what the model is (and, of course, that's bad too).
 
 Given our disagreement and my attempt at clarification above, if that
 does not convince you and/or Shriram and/or Todd that (a) may be a bad
 idea, then I'll just go with it. Esp. considering that teachpacks in
 this manner are something we are moving away from.
 
 Robby
